##The Multi-AZ Fleet & Stateful Storage

Description
Scenario:

You are migrating a legacy monolithic application to AWS. The architecture board demands that the new deployment eliminates single points of failure by spanning across multiple physical data centers (Availability Zones).

Furthermore, the application writes critical transaction logs locally. Since EC2 instances are ephemeral and can be terminated at any time, you must decouple the storage from the compute.

Your Mission:

Deploy a highly available fleet of two web servers spread across two distinct Availability Zones in the Oregon (us-west-2) region. You must attach a secondary, stateful EBS volume to each instance. To prove the infrastructure is fully automated, you must use a bootstrap script (User Data) to automatically format the new volume, mount it to /data, persist the mount across reboots, and serve a web page.

Requirements:

1. Security Configuration:

Create a Security Group named ha-fleet-sg that allows inbound HTTP (80) and SSH (22) from Anywhere (0.0.0.0/0).
2. Multi-AZ Compute Provisioning:

Launch Server A in the us-west-2a Availability Zone. Name it exactly server-az-a.
Launch Server B in the us-west-2b Availability Zone. Name it exactly server-az-b.
Both servers must use Amazon Linux 2023 and the t3.micro instance type.
3. Stateful Storage Integration:

During the launch configuration, leave the default Root Volume at 8 GiB.
Add a New Volume (EBS gp2, 8 GiB) to both instances.
4. Automated Bootstrapping:

Write a User Data shell script that executes on boot for both servers. You can research around on how to achieve this.

The script must:

Install, start, and enable the Apache web server (httpd).

Identify the attached secondary EBS volume (on t3.micro instances, this is /dev/nvme1n1).

Format the volume using the xfs filesystem.

Create a directory at /data and mount the volume to it.

Add an entry to /etc/fstab with the nofail parameter to ensure the mount survives reboots.

Write an HTML file to /var/www/html/index.html indicating the server name and confirming the storage is mounted.

Outcome
Mastered Multi-AZ Deployments to survive localized physical data center failures.

Implemented Compute and Storage Decoupling by attaching and configuring secondary EBS volumes.

Automated Linux OS-level disk management (mkfs, mount, fstab) via EC2 User Data.



Answer--

#!/bin/bash

# Update system
dnf update -y

# Install Apache
dnf install -y httpd

# Start and enable Apache
systemctl enable httpd
systemctl start httpd

# Secondary EBS volume
DEVICE="/dev/nvme1n1"

# Wait until volume is attached
while [ ! -b $DEVICE ]; do
    sleep 5
done

# Format only if filesystem does not exist
if ! blkid $DEVICE; then
    mkfs.xfs $DEVICE
fi

# Create mount point
mkdir -p /data

# Get UUID
UUID=$(blkid -s UUID -o value $DEVICE)

# Add to fstab if not already present
grep -q "$UUID" /etc/fstab || echo "UUID=$UUID /data xfs defaults,nofail 0 2" >> /etc/fstab

# Mount filesystem
mount -a

# Create web page
cat > /var/www/html/index.html <<EOF
<html>
<head><title>HA Fleet Server A</title></head>
<body>
<h1>server-az-a</h1>
<p>Apache is running successfully.</p>
<p>Secondary EBS volume mounted on /data.</p>
</body>
</html>
EOF

systemctl restart httpd

